<dl id="n36166a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36166a">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36166a"> 166(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> teawidow pension ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36166a"><li>FW 545.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36166a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36166a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36166a">MS BL 47484b-460</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:207 <a name="rBd14y" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36166a">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">She also has 5s. per week from a &ldquo;<mark>Tea Pension</mark>&rdquo;. (A Tea Company started a scheme under which a regular purchaser of a &frac14; pound of their tea per week on being left a widow is entitled to a pension of 5s. per week during her widowhood, the only apparent condition for the continuation of this pension being that she continues to buy the regular quantity of tea each week.) <small> B. Seebohm Rowntree, <a name="BSRP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BSRP"><cite title="source">Poverty, A Study of Town Life</cite></a>, 3rd ed.? (1922) 317</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
